Abstract.

We construct Calabi-Yau threefolds defined over â„šâ„š{\mathbb{Q}} via quotients of abelian threefolds, and re-verify the rigid Calabi-Yau threefolds in this construction are modular by computing their L-series, without [8] or [12]. We compute the intermediate Jacobians of the rigid Calabi-Yau threefolds as complex tori, then compute a â„šâ„š{\mathbb{Q}}-model for the 1-torus given a â„šâ„š{\mathbb{Q}}-structure on the rigid Calabi-Yau threefolds, and find infinitely many examples and counterexamples for a conjecture of Yui about the relation between the Lğ¿L-series of the rigid Calabi-Yau threefolds and the Lğ¿L-series of their intermediate Jacobians.

Thus, for a curve Cğ¶C, the only intermediate Jacobian is J1â€‹(C)superscriptğ½1ğ¶J^{1}(C), which is the Jacobian variety of the curve. We will be interested mostly in Calabi-Yau varieties, so for the one-dimensional case we have elliptic curves which are known to be isomorphic to their (intermediate) Jacobians, and these are all the possibilities. For two dimensional examples one has K3 surfaces which have trivial first and third cohomology, hence no-non-trivial intermediate Jacobians, and so our focus will be with Calabi-Yau threefolds. Not much is known about these varieties, but they are very useful tools. As complex varieties one has e.g., [5] who used the intermediate Jacobian of a cubic threefold to show there exist unirational varieties that are not rational, and [24] where intermediate Jacobians are used to show the Griffiths group of a general member in a family of non-rigid Calabi-Yau threefolds is infinite dimensional. An interest in the physics literature comes from the use of Calabi-Yau varieties in string theory, e.g., in [1], [7] and [17]. As Xğ‘‹X is KÃ¤hler we have that the intermediate Jacobian is a complex torus of dimension 1+h1,2â€‹(X)1superscriptâ„12ğ‘‹1+h^{1,2}(X). Thus, when Xğ‘‹X is rigid, J2â€‹(X)superscriptğ½2ğ‘‹J^{2}(X) is a 1-torus, possibly with a canonical structure of an elliptic curve.

The work to date studies the geometry of Jâ€‹(X)ğ½ğ‘‹J(X), i.e., the complex structure. However, as intermediate Jacobians generalize the classical Jacobian variety of a curve, as well as the Picard varieties and Albanese varieties of any nğ‘›n-dimensional varieties, it is natural to ask if one can study arithmetic on all intermediate Jacobians by finding a canonical â„šâ„š{\mathbb{Q}}-structure when Xğ‘‹X is defined over â„šâ„š{\mathbb{Q}}. All of our examples of Calabi-Yau threefolds will be defined over â„šâ„š{\mathbb{Q}}, but one can similarly try to associate a canonical Kğ¾K-structure for any number field Kğ¾K if Xğ‘‹X is defined over Kğ¾K instead. We will construct some rigid Calabi-Yau threefolds in which we are able to compute their intermediate Jacobians as complex varieties, and then refine this computation to give a natural â„šâ„š{\mathbb{Q}}-structure as well, given a choice of model for the Calabi-Yau threefolds defined over â„šâ„š{\mathbb{Q}}.

Shafarevich conjectures that every variety of CM-type (meaning its Hodge group is abelian) has the Lğ¿L-series of a Grossencharacter, a Hecke Lğ¿L-series, and Borcea shows that a rigid Calabi-Yau threefold with CM-type has a CM elliptic curve as its intermediate Jacobian, which is well known to have a Hecke Lğ¿L-series. Thus, if the conjecture is true, it is a natural question to ask if there is any relation between the associated Grossencharacters of a rigid Calabi-Yau threefold and its intermediate Jacobian. The motivation for the current work is to study a precise conjecture of Yui to this effect.

Conjecture 1 (Yui, [26]).

Let Xğ‘‹X be a rigid Calabi-Yau threefold of CM-type defined over a number field Fğ¹F. Then the intermediate Jacobian J2â€‹(X)superscriptğ½2ğ‘‹J^{2}(X) is an elliptic curve with CM by an imaginary quadratic field Kğ¾K, and has a model defined over the number field Fğ¹F.

then

Lâ€‹(X,s)={Lâ€‹(Ï‡3,s)â€‹Lâ€‹(Ï‡Â¯3,s)ifâ€‹KâŠ‚F,Lâ€‹(Ï‡3,s)otherwise.ğ¿ğ‘‹ğ‘ casesğ¿superscriptğœ’3ğ‘ ğ¿superscriptÂ¯ğœ’3ğ‘ ifğ¾ğ¹ğ¿superscriptğœ’3ğ‘ otherwise.L(X,s)=\left\{\begin{array}[]{ll}L(\chi^{3},s)L(\overline{\chi}^{3},s)&\text{if}\ K\subset F,\\ L(\chi^{3},s)&\text{otherwise.}\end{array}\right.

Consequently, Xğ‘‹X is modular.

We will show that many of our rigid Calabi-Yau threefolds of CM-type satisfy this conjecture, but not all. In particular, we will show that if one of our examples, Xğ‘‹X, satisfies the conjecture, then all quadratic twists of Xğ‘‹X satisfy the conjecture, while all non-quadratic twists of Xğ‘‹X do not. After this we generalize our construction to Calabi-Yau nğ‘›n-folds and show that for infinitely many nğ‘›n satisfying a congruence with the order of the CM automorphisms we have the natural generalization of the conjecture is true. Similarly, for infinitely many nğ‘›n the conjecture will not be true because of the CM twists on the varieties.

We start by constructing our varieties and studying their geometry over â„‚â„‚{\mathbb{C}}. We use a generalized Borcea construction of Calabi-Yau threefolds using (finite) quotients of products of elliptic curves, and determine which quotients give rigid Calabi-Yau threefolds. We then choose a â„šâ„š{\mathbb{Q}}-structure for the Calabi-Yau threefolds, via the underlying elliptic curves, and compute their respective Lğ¿L-series. Once this is done we compute the intermediate Jacobians as complex tori, and then over â„šâ„š{\mathbb{Q}}, via the choice of â„šâ„š{\mathbb{Q}}-structure given on the threefolds. We are then able to compare the Lğ¿L-series of the intermediate Jacobians and their respective threefolds and check the conjecture.

Our construction also gives rise to non-rigid Calabi-Yau threefolds, which we leave to future work [15], as the intermediate Jacobians are no longer elliptic curves, and the arithmetic of 2-tori and 4-tori is more complicated. Moreover, the question of modularity (automorphy) is nowhere near as resolved, as [8] and [12] no longer apply.

Remark.
